I had such a lovely weekend I just wanted to write it down. <!-- more --> I told my boyfriend on Wednesday that I wanted to take him on a date Friday night - we planned for a dinner at one of our fav vegan restaurants and then seeing Free Solo afterwards. I ended up coming over with a bottle of wine already wearing my pajamas with my heating pad in tow for the neck pain he was having. We cuddled up on the couch and he ordered us vegetable fried rice and we watched Moon on Netflix. Such a simple evening but it was so so nice and cozy with the rain and chill outside and the warmth and love inside. (Was that? like?way too cheesy? lol) I woke up before him and got my stuff around to go home and go on a run because I skipped it Friday night. Easy 3.5 miles in the rain and wind on super tired muscles. One of those runs that you‚Äôre immediately over before it even starts - I just needed 35 minutes on my feet and I got it, but I did not enjoy it! lol But sometimes that‚Äôs how it goes. Run and done. Ate yummy breakfast with hot delicious coffee & showered. Then I got all nice to go out with my boyfriend! I don‚Äôt wear makeup to work so getting ready to go out on the weekends is always a treat for me to spend some extra time on myself. Then we went to the camera store downtown where we bought film for our cameras! We got three rolls each. He checked out some more equipment then we were off to the restaurant for dinner. We got there right at five when they opened for dinner and we were the only ones in there for maybe ten minutes then it filled up pretty quickly and we were surrounded by other couples and families. We ordered an appetizer and it was SO delicious! It was some kind of red lentil pecan pate and oh my goodness!! Then we got our dinners - he got a Mexican-inspired dish and I got a portobello wellington plate and we were both pleased as punch. I was so full but when the waitress brought the dessert menu we couldn‚Äôt help but look?and then ordered the plum quince crisp with vegan vanilla ice cream. So. Good. We left the restaurant and tried to make our movie, but it was sold out when we got there! We were both a bit disappointed but we arranged to see it another time this week. I drove us back to my apartment and we fed Joe and hung out with him for a bit, gave him lots of scratches and pets, then grabbed another bottle of wine and some frozen waffles for the morning and went back to his place. (He‚Äôs allergic to cats. *cue tears* lol) We got into our jammies and while he watched the last two episodes of House of Cards I played with my camera and worked on my embroidery and repaired a button on his duvet cover for him. I took two photos of him on my new camera (my first photos ever on the camera!) and then after he was done watching his episodes we finished Moon. We were in such goofy moods because of the wine and funny conversations we‚Äôd had throughout the day, I was having so much fun. I took my make up off, brushed my teeth and hopped into bed where we were happy to know we‚Äôd get an extra hour of sleep because of daylight savings. We woke up and cuddled for a bit before rolling out of bed to make breakfast. He made us coffee (in the Chemex I bought him for his birthday, he loves it!) and then he made us waffles. We ate on the couch watching the office :) a great Sunday morning. I asked him if he still wanted to go downtown to see about this wood slab sale. We got dressed and headed out. I brought my camera just in case. Before we went home he asked if I wanted to go to the farmer‚Äôs market. I‚Äôm a red-blooded American girl so of course I said yes. We saw? SO MANY DOGS!!!! Delirium Inspired by the moments of deep dreams where the space enters abtraccion mode or basic graphics in which we are panic state to have no control of the suffering of the material transformation and culminates in contemplating movement of the entities Onirism or dream delirium Onirism is usually characterized by visual hallucinations, but may also be accompanied by those that involve the sense of touch and very rarely also includes auditory hallucinations. There are more complex combinations of onirism formed by hallucinations that involve several senses, which are called with the term ‚Äúdream delirium? Applied to Art It is worth mentioning that the term onirism can be seen and analyzed from an artistic perspective. In this way it can even be considered as a process of abstraction and synthesis, in which the artist is stimulated by reality, which he internalizes by choosing (arbitrarily or heuristically) certain details or events external to him or her, which he studies, remember, in some way he ponders or treasures them and finally reflects them in his work to share them with others. So we have that the artist uses and is used to interpret his dream or dream hallucinations, allusions, similes, metaphors, signs, and symbols. In specific cases: when words are used, then it is Literary Onirism; when images are used then it is Pictorial Onirism; when tangible forms (sculpture, jewelry, dance, ballet) are used, it is Plastic Onirism.
